**History**

While the term "mashup" might evoke a more contemporary image, its conceptual precursors and early manifestations can be found much earlier. A pivotal, though perhaps not explicitly labeled as such at the time, example is [Harry Nilsson](/Harry_Nilsson)'s 1967 album [Pandemonium Shadow Show](/Pandemonium_Shadow_Show). Within this album, Nilsson's rendition of "[You Can't Do That](/You_Can%27t_Do_That)" by [the Beatles](/The_Beatles) is not a straightforward cover. Instead, Nilsson meticulously recreated his own vocal performances of over a dozen Beatles songs, weaving them into a singular track. [5] The genesis of this unique approach, as Nilsson himself described, stemmed from a simple guitar chord that, in his realization, could serve as the foundation for numerous Beatles melodies. [6] This innovative recording has led some to credit Harry Nilsson as the progenitor of the mashup.

However, the lineage of the mashup extends further back, with several other recordings considered early examples or direct precursors. [Bill Buchanan](/Bill_Buchanan_(songwriter)) and [Dickie Goodman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dickie_Goodman)'s 1956 track "[The Flying Saucer](/The_Flying_Saucer_(song))" is frequently cited. [7] [8] [Marshall McLuhan](/Marshall_McLuhan)'s spoken-word album [The Medium Is the Massage](/The_Medium_Is_the_Massage_(album)) from 1967, [10] and the [John Benson Brooks Trio](/John_Benson_Brooks)'s experimental [Avant Slant](/Avant_Slant) from 1968, also exhibit qualities of sonic amalgamation. [10] The burgeoning [hip hop](/Hip_hop_music) scene contributed significantly, with [Grandmaster Flash](/Grandmaster_Flash)'s 1981 track "[The Adventures of Grandmaster Flash on the Wheels of Steel](/The_Adventures_of_Grandmaster_Flash_on_the_Wheels_of_Steel)" being a prime example of live manipulation and blending of existing records. [11] [12] [13] Even [Paul McCartney](/Paul_McCartney) dabbled in the concept with his 1983 track "Tug of Peace," [14] as did [Climie Fisher](/Climie_Fisher) with the "Hip Hop Mix" of "[Rise to the Occasion](/Rise_to_the_Occasion_(Climie_Fisher_song))" in 1987. [15] The novelty act [Jive Bunny and the Mastermixers](/Jive_Bunny_and_the_Mastermixers) achieved significant success with their 1989 album [Jive Bunny: The Album](/Jive_Bunny:_The_Album), [16] and the influential electronic act [Coldcut](/Coldcut) released "[Journeys by DJ: 70 Minutes of Madness](/Journeys_by_DJ:_70_Minutes_of_Madness)" in 1995, a pioneering work in the DJ mix format that heavily incorporated sampled and blended material. [17] [18]

While its title suggests a medley, the 1983 track "[Do It Again Medley with Billie Jean](/Do_It_Again_Medley_with_Billie_Jean)" by the Italian music project [Club House](/Club_House_(band)) is often regarded as one of the earliest commercially released mashups. This track masterfully combined elements of [Steely Dan](/Steely_Dan)'s 1973 hit "[Do It Again](/Do_It_Again_(Steely_Dan_song))" with [Michael Jackson](/Michael_Jackson)'s contemporaneous chart-topper, "[Billie Jean](/Billie_Jean)". The song achieved considerable success, reaching number 11 in the UK and charting within the top 10 in Belgium, Ireland, and the Netherlands. [19]

Another noteworthy early example emerged in 1985 with [the Tubes](/The_Tubes)' studio album, [Love Bomb](/Love_Bomb_(The_Tubes_album)). The second side of this album featured the track "Theme from a Wooly Place," which ingeniously juxtaposed the tune "[Wooly Bully](/Wooly_Bully)" in one audio channel with "[Theme from A Summer Place](/Theme_from_A_Summer_Place)" in the other. [21]

The year 1990 marked a significant milestone when [Norman Cook](/Norman_Cook), under his alias [Beats International](/Beats_International), secured the number one spot on the [UK Singles Chart](/UK_Singles_Chart) with "[Dub Be Good to Me](/Dub_Be_Good_to_Me)". This track was, in essence, a mashup that re-recorded vocals from [the SOS Band](/The_SOS_Band)'s "[Just Be Good to Me](/Just_Be_Good_to_Me)" and layered them over the instrumental backing of [the Clash](/The_Clash)'s "[The Guns of Brixton](/The_Guns_of_Brixton)". This achievement signified the first mashup to gain substantial mainstream recognition. [22] [23]

In 1990, [John Zorn](/John_Zorn)'s album [Naked City](/Naked_City_(album)) presented a bold reinterpretation of [Ornette Coleman](/Ornette_Coleman)'s "[Lonely Woman](/Lonely_Woman_(composition))", setting it against the iconic bassline of [Roy Orbison](/Roy_Orbison)'s "[Pretty Woman](/Pretty_Woman_(song))". [24] [importance of example(s)?](/Template:Refexample)

Anticipating the surge in mashup popularity during the 2000s, German trance act [Fragma](/Fragma) experienced immense success with "[Toca's Miracle](/Toca%27s_Miracle)". This track, a mashup of their earlier single "Toca Me" and [Coco Star](/Coco_Star)'s 1996 hit "I Need a Miracle," was initially created by British DJ Vimto in 1999. "[Toca's Miracle]" topped the UK charts and reached the top 10 in Australia and across Europe. [25]

The mashup movement experienced a resurgence in 2001 with the release of [As Heard on Radio Soulwax Pt. 2](/As_Heard_on_Radio_Soulwax_Pt._2) by [Soulwax](/Soulwax)'s Dewaele brothers, a meticulously crafted blend of 45 distinct tracks. In the same year, a remix of [Christina Aguilera](/Christina_Aguilera)'s "[Genie in a Bottle](/Genie_in_a_Bottle)" by [Freelance Hellraiser](/Freelance_Hellraiser) gained considerable attention. This remix ingeniously paired Aguilera's vocals with the distinctive guitar riff from "[Hard to Explain](/Hard_to_Explain)" by New York band [the Strokes](/The_Strokes), under the title "A Stroke of Genie-us." [26]

In 2001, English producer [Richard X](/Richard_X) created a clandestine mashup that blended [Adina Howard](/Adina_Howard)'s "[Freak Like Me](/Freak_Like_Me)" with [Tubeway Army](/Tubeway_Army)'s "[Are "Friends" Electric?](/Are_%22Friends%22_Electric%3F)". Titled "We Don't Give a Damn About Our Friends," this track became a popular underground dance anthem under his alias Girls on Top. Due to difficulties in securing permission for the original vocals for commercial release, Richard X enlisted the English girl group [Sugababes](/Sugababes) to re-record the vocals. Released in April 2002, this version propelled the Sugababes to their first UK number one single and brought significant recognition and mainstream appeal to the mashup genre. Richard X continued his success with two more top 10 hits: "[Being Nobody](/Being_Nobody)" (number 3), which combined the vocals of [Chaka Khan](/Chaka_Khan) and [Rufus (band)](/Rufus_(band))'s "[Ain't Nobody](/Ain%27t_Nobody)" with the instrumental of [the Human League](/The_Human_League)'s "[Being Boiled](/Being_Boiled)" and featured [Liberty X](/Liberty_X), and "[Finest Dreams](/Finest_Dreams)" (number 8), where American vocalist [Kelis](/Kelis) sang the vocals from the SOS Band's "[The Finest](/The_Finest_(song))" over the instrumental from the Human League's "[The Things That Dreams Are Made Of](/The_Things_That_Dreams_Are_Made_Of)".

At the [2002 Brit Awards](/2002_Brit_Awards), held on February 20, 2002, Australian pop singer [Kylie Minogue](/Kylie_Minogue) delivered a memorable performance that fused her number one hit "[Can't Get You Out of My Head](/Can%27t_Get_You_Out_of_My_Head)" with [New Order](/New_Order_(band))'s seminal track "[Blue Monday](/Blue_Monday_(New_Order_song))". This live rendition is widely considered one of the first instances of a mainstream artist utilizing a mashup in a performance setting. It was later ranked at number 40 on [The Guardian](/The_Guardian)'s comprehensive 2011 list detailing 50 Key Events in the History of Dance Music. [27] The mashup itself, christened "Can't Get Blue Monday Out of My Head," was subsequently released as the B-side to Minogue's single "[Love at First Sight](/Love_at_First_Sight_(Kylie_Minogue_song))" and was later included on her 2008 remix album [Boombox](/Boombox_(Kylie_Minogue_album)). In the years following this event, mashups became an increasingly common tool for major artists in their live shows, particularly as a means to contemporize older material and align it with the thematic and sonic qualities of their newer work. For instance, during her 2006 [Confessions Tour](/Confessions_Tour), [Madonna](/Madonna) integrated elements of [the Trammps](/The_Trammps)'s "[Disco Inferno](/Disco_Inferno)" into her performance of her 2000 hit "[Music](/Music_(Madonna_song))", effectively bridging the gap between the songs and enhancing the tour's overarching disco theme. On her 2008 [Sticky & Sweet Tour](/Sticky_%26_Sweet_Tour), she performed a mashup of her 1990 anthem "[Vogue](/Vogue_(Madonna_song))" with the instrumental backing of her then-recent single "[4 Minutes](/4_Minutes_(song))", thereby updating the classic track with the more urban sonic palette of her [Hard Candy](/Hard_Candy_(Madonna_album)) album.

In August 2003, Madonna's single "[Hollywood](/Hollywood_(Madonna_song))" was remixed and combined with "[Into the Groove](/Into_the_Groove)" for a performance with [Missy Elliott](/Missy_Elliott) under the title "Into the Hollywood Groove." This collaboration, part of a promotional campaign for the clothing retailer [GAP](/Gap_(clothing_retailer)), drew criticism for what some perceived as the commercial exploitation of the [underground culture](/Underground_culture) surrounding mashups. [28]

Launched in San Francisco in 2003, [Bootie](/Bootie_(club_night)) emerged as the first recurring club night in the United States exclusively dedicated to the burgeoning art form of the bootleg mashup. By 2019, the event had expanded its reach, hosting monthly parties in numerous cities worldwide, including Los Angeles, Paris, Boston, Munich, and New York City. The party's memorable slogan, "Music for the A.D.D. Generation," even inspired the creation of "A.D.D," Israel's inaugural party focused solely on mashups. [29] The "Best of Bootie" mashup compilation series, produced by Bootie founders [A Plus D](/A_Plus_D), became an annual internet sensation. Released every December since 2005, each compilation garnered immense popularity, with the downloads requiring substantial bandwidth, often exceeding 5,000 GB. [30]

Despite the fact that mashups largely remained in the underground, with only a few exceptions gaining widespread notice (such as the works of [DJ Cummerbund](/DJ_Cummerbund) [31] and Bill McClintock [32]), the practice of remixing other artists' music without prior consent has persisted. The increasing difficulty in maintaining visibility online, due to automated copyright detection systems like [Content ID](/Content_ID) and cease and desist orders from original artists, has made it challenging for these creations to remain accessible. [33]

**Live Mashups**

[DJs](/Disc_jockey) possess the capability to construct mashups in real-time during live performances. This involves the selective integration of various song components, such as instrumental passages, vocal lines, and drum beats, drawn from multiple tracks. This technique can be executed with music released in a [stem format](/List_of_musical_works_released_in_a_stem_format) or with audio processed through [stem separation](/Stem_separation) technology. Prominent DJ software that offers stem separation capabilities includes [Rekordbox](/Rekordbox), [Serato DJ](/Serato), [VirtualDJ](/VirtualDJ), [Djay](/Djay_(software)), [Traktor](/Traktor), and Engine DJ. [34]

**Video Games**

The concept of mashups has also been integrated into the realm of video games. [DJ Hero](/DJ_Hero), a rhythm game developed by [Activision](/Activision) and released in 2009, featured over 90 pre-made mashups, challenging players to hit notes on a turntable controller to score points. [35]

More recently, [Fuser](/Fuser_(video_game)), released in 2020 by [Harmonix](/Harmonix), provides players with the tools to create their own mashups using over 100 songs. The game allows users to combine four [instrument stems](/Stem_(audio)) from the [master recording](/Multitrack_recording) of various tracks. [36]

In December 2023, [Fortnite](/Fortnite) introduced a new game mode called [Fortnite Festival](/Fortnite_Festival). Within the Jam Stage and [Fortnite Battle Royale](/Fortnite_Battle_Royale) modes, players are now able to create mashups using a library of over 100 songs.

